description:
Deceased.

This duckling was an apparent victim to a predator, with its head and leg being torn from the body. The detached leg sat next to the rest of the carcass but I was unable to find the head.  

I think this is a Mallard rather than a goose as at this point, the Canada Goose Goslings were already much larger than the corpse. A family of Mallards frequented the area and the ducklings were a closer match in size. The darker contrast between the back and belly also seems to suggest a Mallard. 

The dead duckling was gone by my next visit to the pond.

description: This is a unfortunate story. We observed this LTDU struggle, in the middle of the road. It would sit down, then waddle, sit dow, than waddle. We scared it off to the side and called some of the Old Cut staff to pick it up. As we we're walking down the road, we noticed a truck going down the road- and the Long-tailed had ventured back onto the road. We started walking back quickly waving our arms so the driver would know about the duck. I wasn't too worried- the duck was in plain sight. As the truck approached, it slowed down, then veered towards the duck and sped up, running it over. The driver obviously knew about the duck, but felt fine, great even, about killing it. The duck was sick, and would've probably died, but that's no way no end a life. Such a shame.
